node.text: Grateful for all of these traumatic experiences because they shaped me to be more empathetic, compassionate and purpose-driven.. ultimately more like Jesus. I wrote The Abundant Life Devotional Journal hoping that it would help others heal as well. You can actually look inside the journal at TheHoogaShop.com! @thehoogashop It’s available to ship to most countries. I truly hope it blesses you. 🙏🏼

node.text:
After years of praying, working hard and saving my earnings, I finally gave my mom an early retirement. This week, we moved her into a beautiful apartment down the street from where I live. She loves the amenities and location so far. She was opposed to moving at first, but I think she's slowly learning that there's freedom in being in a safe place. I can't wait to keep you all updated on our journey!

Watch the full video: https://youtu.be/s_1K8b0qxfc

The video you’re listening to covers the third fold, your vocational purpose.

You can sign up at www.girlandtheword.com/theabundantlife to start watching these idyllic and edifying videos today! There are 30 videos total— each one around 15 minutes long, with enriching insights and visuals to help you live a more peaceful and abundant life.

node.text:
I’ve been learning more about envy lately, and the reality is quite dark. Envy is different than jealousy. Jealousy is protectiveness over what is rightfully yours. Envy is resentfulness over what is not yours. Envy leads to gossip, bitterness, contempt, and even rage. In many cultures (obviously not the American culture), people actually fear being envied. When you are the object of envy, people look for reasons to hate you and wish for your downfall, even if they have nothing to gain from it. Yet, many people still WANT to be envied because they think it would mean that they would be loved. In reality, being envied is quite the opposite of being loved. Envy is a terrible thing for both the envier and the envied.

One of the best ways to guard your heart against envy is to practice having the abundant mindset. The abundant mindset is knowing that you already have everything you need today to glorify the Lord. Even if you’re lacking something, you have hope that He will make a way for you in His perfect timing. Hope and faith in God’s provision defers envy.

When you have an abundant mindset, you can be genuinely happy for others and not envy what they have because you yourself do not feel any lack. You won’t have contempt for those who have more than you because you no longer feel that gnawing sense of emptiness. You can practice “spiritual object constancy”—which is the ability to maintain the feeling of being loved and provided for by God even when you don’t physically feel His presence. You can be made full and complete by the Holy Spirit, rather than by earthly things. This is the abundant life that you’ve been called to. Are you ready to embrace it?

This not only means that we would have to pay double rent and mortgage for a longer period of time, but the home renovations content that you guys have been waiting for is also on hold. 

Yet, I’ve already seen so many fruits that have come from this season of waiting. I’ve had more time to focus on @thehoogashop, work on my character before we have children, and grow in my intimacy with Jon. This forced break that the Lord has given us turned out to be the biggest blessing. I truly feel like He is preparing us for what’s ahead!

Do you ever get that feeling… when life doesn’t go your way but you just know that God is up to something good? I’m just grateful that He cares enough to slow us down before we burnt ourselves out. Worthy goals always take preparation! ❤️🙏🏼

node.text:
Would you describe yourself as a jealous person? I know, I started off pretty strong there! Never been one for small talk. But seriously—would you honestly say that you struggle with covetousness? I’m willing to bet that most people do, without realizing it. It doesn’t help that these social platforms were designed to profit off our jealousy, insecurities, and comparison. I didn’t think of myself as a jealous person until I really thought about what the term, “covet,” meant. It is the desire to possess something that isn’t yours, whether it’s someone else’s success, financial status, relationship, joy, fulfillment—or the whole shebang.

We’ve all felt the sting of envy before, but did you know that envy has a kryptonite? It’s contentment. Sheer, blissful contentment. It’s forcing your mind to do away with thoughts of lack and dwell only on thoughts of abundance. It’s reframing the challenges in your life as a stepping stone to character growth and success. It’s believing that God has already given you everything you need at this moment to glorify Him.

So, the next time you find yourself pouring over someone’s IG and going green with envy, just close the app, open a notepad, and write down 3 blessings you DO have. This is your lot in this season, and this is your story. It’s the best story for you, and it’s not even over yet. God wrote this unique journey just for you. His gifts for you are so good, don’t you see it? ❤️🙏🏼
